@startuml Result_CppToRust_Integration

!theme bluegray
!pragma teoz true

participant "C++ Code" as cpp
participant "FFI Boundary" as ffi
participant "Rust Code" as rust

autonumber

cpp -> cpp: SomeFunction() returns\nResult
note over cpp
  local variable created:
  bmw::Result result
  {
    storage.value = true,
    discriminant = 0  // Value
  }
end note

cpp -> cpp: Prepare to return\nby value across FFI

cpp -> ffi: Return Result\n(by register/stack)
note over ffi, cpp
  **ABI Calling Convention:**
  Registers/stack contain:
  - Offset 0: bool value (1 byte) = 0x01
  - Offset 1-3: padding
  - Offset 4-7: ErrorCode (4 bytes) = 0
  - Offset 8-15: domain pointer
  - Offset 16-23: message.ptr
  - Offset 24-31: message.len
  - Offset 32: discriminant = 0x00
end note

ffi -> rust: Receive as ffi::Expected
note over rust
  Rust sees the incoming bytes:
  struct Expected {
    storage: union {
      value: bool = 0x01,
      error: Error = {...}
    },
    discriminant: u8 = 0x00
  }
end note

rust -> rust: Match on discriminant
alt discriminant == 0x00 (Value)
    rust -> rust: Extract bool value
    note over rust
      unsafe {
        ManuallyDrop::take(&mut storage.value)
      }
      Retrieves: true
    end note

    rust -> rust: Mark discriminant = 255 (Stale)

    rust -> rust: Construct Ok(true)
    note over rust
      std::result::Result = Ok(true)
    end note

else discriminant == 0x01 (Error)
    rust -> rust: Extract Error
    note over rust
      Would construct Err(error)
    end note
end

opt discriminant != 255 (not stale)
    note over rust
      Clean up original storage
      to avoid leaks.
      The union may contain either
      a Value or an Error. In any
      case, we must drop it properly.
      If the discriminant is stale (255),
      we don't have to do it because the
      Rust object took ownership, and thus
      will clean it up later.
    end note

    rust -> rust: Value::Drop or Error::Drop
end

rust -> rust: Call match on Rust Result
note over rust
  match rust_result {
      Ok(bool_val) => {
          println!("Success: {}", bool_val);
      },
      Err(err) => {
          eprintln!("Failed: {}", err);
      }
  }
end note

rust -> rust: Process success path
note over rust
  Application logic for Ok case
  Uses bool_val = true
end note

@enduml
